On 5/10/05 10:53 PM, "Richard" <cathrich(-at-)tpg.com.au> wrote:

> All the type 4 case's I've seen only have ONE relief in the oil gallery, the
> one which is next to the oil filter (AP and CJ motors). The Bentley shows in
> the oil circuit two relief's. So, is it common to have two reliefs in the
> circuit?

The solid lifter cases are dual relief, hydraulic lifter are single.

#47 in this diagram is the second one:

http://www.ratwell.com/technical/Microfiche/t200710.gif

>In the case's I have with one relief, which relief is the one next to
> the oil filter? (the relief to bypass cooler, or the relief from the oil
> gallery to the sump). Or is the circuit for the single relief case different
> all together?

The one by the oil filter is the oil pressure relief valve. The one on the
other side of the case is the oil control valve:

http://homepage.mac.com/ratwell/.Pictures/Parts72Bus1/37-OilControlValve.jpg

> Next is the cooling fan on the end of the crank. Is the fan and maybe even the
> fan housing different on the vanagon air cooled motors? I've never seen one so
> don't know.

I'm not sure if the hub is different but the castings of the fan are
different.

